snippet:
We had our wedding reception here nine years ago. Since then, we’ve come back every anniversary. Not as a ritual we force ourselves to keep, but because it’s the easiest decision we make all year.

The thing that keeps pulling us back is not just the food, though it’s always excellent. It’s the feeling that nothing has slipped. The service still feels attentive in a human way. The management still seems to care about how the room feels, not just how full it is. The menu still tastes like it’s being cooked by people who haven’t gotten bored.

D.C. is very good at producing restaurants that feel essential for about eighteen months. Rasika West End has been in my personal top five since 2014. That’s nine years of consistency, which is a far harder flex than novelty.

When friends visit from out of town and ask where they should go, Rasika is always one of the places I recommend without thinking. It’s safe in the best possible way. You will have a great meal. You will be taken care of. You will understand why it’s lasted.

As for my experience, I opted for a takeaway, and frankly, it was disappointing. I sampled all the vegetarian options on the menu, hoping to find at least one standout dish — but none lived up to even average expectations. That said, the environment was lively and buzzing, which might be a draw if you’re looking for a vibrant atmosphere. But let’s be real — no amount of ambience can make up for a bad meal when you’re genuinely hungry.

Bottom line: If you’re in it for good food — especially vegetarian — you’re better off trying another restaurant. This one is style over substance.

snippet:
So, I’ve had Rasika on my list for quite some time now and finally had the opportunity to try them (the Dupont Circle location).

We came here for an early dinner and sat on the patio and had a beautiful experience!

For appetizers, we tried the Mango Shrimp and the Sweet Potato Samosa which were absolutely delicious. Both dishes were flavored well and left us wanting more, however, we were saving room for the entrees.

For my main dish, I had the Chicken Tikka Masala with some Garlic Naan, which were okay. I think I was expecting a little more umph for the chicken and more garlic for naan.

The service here was also really good. Our waiter gave his honest POV for dish recommendations, which I thoroughly appreciated. I just wish that I would have tried the duck dish that he recommended rather than going to my norm. He also was very thoughtful in honoring our friendship day with their unique dessert!

Overall, great experience. If ever in the area again and craving Indian food, I will definitely opt to go back to try the duck dish.

snippet:
Rasika lives up to its reputation as one of the finest dining experiences for Indian cuisine in DC. The hospitality was exceptional, the presentation of the food was excellent, and even though some of the dishes were disappointing, there was plenty on the menu that we loved.

The Palak Chaat, Mangalorean Chicken, and Chickpeas Khichadi, Pappadums, and the Truffle Naans were our favorites. The fish chilli garlic and reshmi kebabs were also very good.

The lamb biryani was disappointing. Even though the lamb was cooked well, the biryani lacked flavor, and the manager was kind enough to take it off our check.

In the drinks, Sania and Sheela were quite good, but the Asha was forgettable.

In the desserts, we tried the Gulab Jamun and the Kulfi. Both were average and I wouldn't recommend them.

All in all, it was a positive experience where the staff was kind and treated hosts with respect, and the food was generally very good. Highly recommend it!

Update: Visited again and the food lived up to its reputation. However, the Gulab Jamun continued to disappoint. Overall, the review stands even though it is inching closer to 5 stars :)

snippet:
This was recommended by several family members and some of their friends. We made a reservation for indoor seating and were put on the covered patio which we were told would be warm. I was not warm even with several heaters and kept my winter coat on the entire evening. The patio chairs are so extremely uncomfortable. The table behind us was LOUD and their child was obxious with a VERY loud ipad in his lap and his chair pushed out so far from the table that servers were bumping into my back all night with no apology. One almost tripped trying to avoid the heater, him and I.

I ordered a cocktail and my husband had the punch- both were good but not something we would order again. We decided to order the tasting menu and were overall very satisfied- I requested no chicken due to a intolerance and was given a lamb dish as well as a "shrimp" curry. I put quotations around shrimp bc I received one, single shrimp in my bowl. I wouldn't have minded terribly except it was overcooked and not edible with the intestinal tract still attached. My husband and I felt the first 3 dishes were outstanding (sweet potato samosa, some type of pea/potato cracker, and palak chaat). I enjoyed the majority of my entree which was served biriyani style but again wasn't overall impressed with the shrimp (as stated) or lentil dishes. Dessert was wonderful and I enjoyed sampling the 4 items on the plate. I was surprised that our main server didn't ask if we wanted coffee or tea with dessert and never asked if we wanted any additional drinks throughout the evening. The other service staff was prompt, cheerful, and a joy. We would go back but would order off the menu, skip cocktails for wine, and only accept a table indoors.

snippet:
I was a fan of Rasika once and had multiple visits there, but I won't visit it again.
As a person who is familiar with this cuisine, I used to applaud for the new uniqueness they brought through their dishes yet maintaining the bold indian flavors unapologetically, through both veg and non veg menu. Low key was proud of it back then.

During this visit, I was highly disappointed. They started bold with their entrees( Palak chaat and beetroot   goat cheese Tikki), but it all went downhill from then.  The mains were totally bland, no flavor at all, and not even warm. It seems like they dish was ready for long, and they forgot about it.
The dessert was next, and the graph went down again. Kulfi had a cookie at the bottom and was too hard to even pick up and chew. We asked them, replied very rude, saying this is how it is eat or throw it.

Service was quick, but food was a disaster.
As a person who loved Indian cuisine, Rasika became a huge disappointment.

snippet: If you’re looking for authentic Indian food with real Indian taste this isn’t the place for you. Ambience wise it’s pretty good but when it comes to actual food it’s sub-par especially compared to the price they charge for the food. I went in with my family for lunch and ordered paneer-mussalam that came with a side of rice and along with that we ordered garlic naan and veg-biryani. Firstly they took 15 mins to take the order and then more than 40 mins to serve the order. The paneer tasted like rubber and the taste of the gravy was bad, they just added too much cream in it. The rice side appeared to be side of another side dish. The naan was the size of a puri and came cold when it reached our table. On top of that we ordered additional dishes as running order which didn’t arrive for half an hour so we had to cancel it as our appetite was done. Overall if you’re looking to enjoy good Indian food this isn’t the place but if you’re looking for a fancy Indian restaurant with an expensive menu then sure give it a try.

snippet:
Really superb modern Indian dining experience. Incredibly creative dishes expertly served.

We started with the assorted papadam with the trio of chutneys (mango, tomato raisin, and eggplant ginger). Standout was the mango with an honorable mention for the tomato raisin. Papadam was perfectly crisp, and well dried so not oily.

Next was the Masala Crab Cake with mustard seeds, curry leaves, tempered mayo). Creamy and well balanced with a sharp hint of mustard, these were soft and indulgent they could have been eaten with a spoon.

Then it was onto the Truffle Dosa with potatoes and truffle shavings. Soft spicy potatoes nestled inside an elegantly folded dosa, and accompanied with a creamy spread that accented each bite perfectly.

For our entrees, we had the tandoori lamb chops seasoned with mace, cardamom, cashew nuts, and ginger (succulent and extremely flavorful, very tender) and the chicken Tikka masala (the definite standout, it was smokey and creamy and heaven with each bite).  Highly recommend you get a garlic naan to sop up that savory tikka masala sauce!

For our veggies, we had the small portions of the bhindi mulagapodi (sauteed okra with onions, lentils, and sesame seeds), baingan achari (eggplant with fennel seeds, fenugreek), and zucchini corn peanut poriyal (curry leaves, lentils, and coconut). All were good, but the eggplant achari was by far the best.

For dessert, we shared the chocolate samosas with chocolate mint ice cream. It was tremendous, and the delicately crisp samosas paired perfectly with the smokey ice cream.

Cocktails were fine, my Sania (Bourbon, Spiced Pear-infused Honey, Allspice Dram, Lime, Fresh Thyme) was a bit too sweet so I didn't finish it but it was worth a try.

Service was excellent, from start to finish.
